bioghist.p: The Michigan United Conservation Clubs (MUCC) was formed November 9, 1937 in Owosso, Michigan. The organization was created to bring together into a federation various clubs in the state that were interested in conservation issues, particularly in regards to conservation legislation. Thirty-six clubs were represented at the first meeting. Harry Gaines of Grand Rapids was elected to serve as the group's first president. Dues were set at fifteen cents per capita on the membership of each member club.

The organization expanded rapidly, growing to 81 clubs during its first year, and to 143 by the beginning of the Second World War. During this period, some of the clubs disbanded as members were called into military service. By 1944 the number of affiliated clubs had leveled off at 128. It was also during this period that the MUCC formed a magazine committee which began publishing Michigan-Out-of-Doors in 1947. Today the MUCC is the largest statewide conservation organization in the nation.

Though conservation of Michigan's natural resources has always been the primary focus of MUCC's work, the organization has also involved itself in issues concerning outdoor recreation. In earlier years the term outdoor recreation referred mainly to activities such as swimming, camping, hiking, fishing, hunting and the like. In the past two decades the proliferation of vehicles such as motorcycles, all-terrain vehicles (ATV's) and snowmobiles has added an entirely new dimension to the meaning of outdoor recreation. MUCC has taken a leading role in advising the state legislature on both of these matters and has striven to keep up with new trends throughout its fifty-year history.

The education committee is one of the most important of MUCC's standing committees, stemming from the organization's belief that ultimately the most effective method to resolve conservation/recreation issues is through education of the public. Teacher education (in cooperation with the Department of Natural Resources), providing speakers to schools and public gatherings, and a one-week camping/conservation program at the MUCC Boy's Camp are some of the ways in which MUCC aims toward greater public understanding of conservation issues.

At MUCC's annual conventions, members gather to discuss amendments to the organization's bylaws, reports of committees (both standing and ad-hoc), and resolutions, which are then brought before the state legislature if adopted at the convention. Indeed, this is the origin of much of the conservation legislation passed by the Michigan legislature.

scopecontent.p: The records of the Michigan United Conservation Clubs have been divided into the following series: Administration, Committees, Correspondence, District Organizations, Public Relations, Speech File, Topical Files, Publications, Visual Materials, People File, and Scrapbooks.

The Administration series consists of a copy of the organization's constitution, bylaws, and amendments. There are also board of directors meeting minutes, 1965-2004; executive committee meeting minutes, 1962-2001; annual convention agendas, reports, and meeting minutes, 1937-2001; a handbook for MUCC officers, fund-raisers, etc.

scopecontent.p: Committees consist of an alphabetically arranged listing of MUCC committees spanning the years 1959-2001. The material on these committees, some of them standing and others ad-hoc, consists of meeting minutes, correspondence, reports, and memoranda.

scopecontent.p: The Correspondence series is arranged chronologically and consists primarily of copies of outgoing correspondence with a scattering of incoming communications as well as some administrative memoranda and legal materials.

The District Organizations series contains correspondence, meeting minutes, and memoranda from sixteen of the twenty statewide districts that make up the structure of MUCC. These materials span the dates 1970-2000.

Public Relations, 1968-2001, consists of press releases, 1970-2001, five publications written by MUCC members and published by the organization, four folders of miscellaneous brochures, and a wide variety of materials relating to the publication of the MUCC magazine Michigan Out of Doors. The Bentley Library has on microfilm an almost complete run of this magazine, minus some issues destroyed in an office fire. This microfilm has been cataloged separately.

scopecontent.p: The Speech File series contains 123 general speeches that are indexed by the list in the "General Speech Index" folder, and other speeches relating to wildlife management, gun control, etc. There is also a small file of correspondence.

scopecontent.p: Some of the subjects documented in the Topical Files include material on the organization's fiftieth and sixtieth anniversaries, history, Kent County Conservation League, and the case of Michigan v. Paul C. Younger 1949 relating to the right of a conservation officer to search a suspect. Two of the strengths of this series are the Anti-Hunting and Indian Fishing Rights.

scopecontent.p: The Publications series contains a non-contiguous run of the periodical Michigan Out of Doors.

The Visual Materials series contains a variety of photographs depicting various public figures, wildlife, and organizational activities, nine 16 mm films, a videodisc, and a small assortment of slides. The bulk of the photographs are a subseries taken by Richard P. Smith.

scopecontent.p: The People File series contains an alphabetical arrangement of persons affiliated with the MUCC, as well as political figures. The files themselves contain photographs and additional background information sporadically throughout the series. There are two distinct sizes of envelope files (9x6 and 8.5x11) that contain various sizes of photographs.

scopecontent.p: There are two Scrapbooks in this record group. The larger scrapbook contains MUCC awards, newspaper clippings, letters, pamphlets, etc. from around the 1950s and 1960s. The smaller scrapbook (boxed) contains articles, clippings, and some correspondence from 1945-1963 on MUCC/Conservation issues as well as popular culture.
